Microtubules: Once again cited as "tiny qubit lattices" that perform Fourier transforms to decode light into consciousness.
3. Physics & Science Lessons
A. The Bekenstein Bound
The text accurately references the Bekenstein Bound, a limit in physics that states there is a maximum amount of entropy (information) that can be contained within a finite region of space. When this limit is exceeded, a black hole must form.
B. Feynman's Sum over Histories
The text integrates Richard Feynman’s Path Integral Formulation ("Sum over Histories"). In standard physics, a particle takes every possible path, and these paths interfere to create the most likely outcome. Here, the "Sum" is the vector addition of all internal QSVs.
C. Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle
The text offers a geometric explanation for Uncertainty. Since a vector has a fixed length (amplitude), knowing its X-component precisely (Position) forces the Y-component (Momentum) to become uncertain, because they share the same total amplitude. 
